07239nam a22010215i 9783110328165DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20132009gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013956724  a97831103281657 a10.1515/97831103281652doi  a(DE-B1597)211771  a(OCoLC)853265809  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB799 7aPHI0200002bisacsh0481pa100qDE-10104aThe Roar of Awakening :bA Whiteheadian Dialogue Between Western Psychotherapies and Eastern Worldviews /ced. by George Derfer, Zhihe Wang, Michel Weber. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2013] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (243 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aProcess Thought ,x2198-2287 ;v2000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tBibliography -- tNotes -- tI. The View from the East -- tConsciousness: The Vedantic Approach to Life and Reality -- tDual Aspect Framework for Consciousness and Its Implications: West meets East for Sublimation Process -- tThe Paradoxes of Radical Asceticism: Jainism as a Therapeutic Paradigm -- tYoga Therapeutics: Philosophical, Scientific, and Humanistic Approaches -- tCan Indian Spiritual Practices Be Used in Psychotherapy? -- tII. Transcultural Dialogue -- tIneradicable Frustration and Liberation in Tiantai Buddhism -- tAn Exploration and Analysis of Chinese Traditional Psychotherapy: On the Integration of Whitehead’s Organic Philosophy -- tThe Kyoto School and Self-Awareness in the Field of the Absolute Nothingness. A Comparison with Whitehead’s Philosophy -- tJung and Hisamatsu Re-envisioning Religiosity: Jungian Psychotherapy and the Kyoto School -- tReconstructing the Meaning of Being Human: A Reinterpretation of Frankl in the Framework of Whitehead’s Philosophy -- tThe Development of Binswanger’s Daseinsanalysis -- tThe Intercultural and Daseinanalytical Psychiatry of Kimura Bin -- tA Certain Form of Psychotherapy (Kenosis, Prajna, Jung, and Hillman) -- tVedanta, Process, and Psychotherapy -- tOn Zen Buddhism -- tTable of Contents -- tProcess Thought0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe primary goal of this volume is to describe the contemporary state of affairs in Western psychotherapy, and to do so in a Whiteheadian spirit: with genuine openness to the relative ways in which creativity, beauty, truth, and peace manifest themselves in various cultural traditions. This Whiteheadian Dialogue explores afresh an important cross-elucidatory path: what have we, and what can be learned from a dialogue with Eastern worldviews? In order to generate meaningful contrasts between these different systems of thought, all the papers address common core issues. On one hand, how does the given system understand the interaction of the individual, society, and nature (or cosmos)? On the other hand, what is the paradigm of all pathology and what is its typical or curative pattern?  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aPhilosophy, Comparative. 0aProcess philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Pragmatism.2bisacsh1 aAnthony, Francis-Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradford, David T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Yingmin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerfer, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGao, Fengqiang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrange, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanaoka, Eiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayashi, Yoshihiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g